4/3/00
  First day in the new Cisco building.  The lab is not set up yet.


4/5/00
  Migration of DSP code to ClearCase platform:
    - Added the customization of statmux code onto the ratemux tree.
      Changed files: defs.h, makefile.
    - Merging of the common directory on the tree trees
      Replaced dspalarm.h, dspmsg.h and pidbuf.h by the version on the RMX tree.
      Note: pidbuf.h on RMX tree has different MAX_AUD_PIDS and Clock
      definitions.  Need to verify whether dpi code works.
    - Update pbmsg.h with the version that Jinbo is working on, with some
      modifications.
      The variable SwitchPidGrpReq:spliceType is renamed to
      SwitchPidGrpReq:timeoutMode.  Jinbo will change his code to use the
      same name as DSP uses.
      The variable SwitchPidGrpReq:timeout is re-typed from Uint32 to Int32
      so the dpi code needs not be changed.  Eventually, no timeout will be
      signalled by setting timeoutMode to DPI_TIMEOUT_NEVER.  Actually this
      new mode definition is already added, but not used in the dpi code yet.
      Checked in this version of pbmsg.h into the RMX tree.
    - Moved other .h files (defs.h, misc.h, msgio.h, tp.h, utils.h) in the
      DPI common directory to the DPI demux directory.
      Also move the corresponding SCCS history files to the demux SCCS
      directory.
    - Renamed hw.cmd back to c6201.lcf.


4/6/00
  System set up.
  BUG1: Hits bypass, when audio PID is specified, picture breakup every few
        seconds.
  REASON: Hits uses AC3 audio, which the Tandberg decoder is not able to decode!


4/7/00
  JC show me a log file with bad PidBuf in countPicTp().  Not sure how to
  handle this.  Recompile latest dpi code (205) for him to re-test.

  One old problem: insufficient rate reduction.  This leads to statmux
    moving back its PCR.  Eventually dpi will run out of PidBufs.
    Need to figure out a long term solution with statmux.

  Another problem: gap in signal (timebase, PCR, DTS, etc).
    What is the long term statmux solution to handle this?


